i## Why Use Sass and Webpack		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSass is a superset of CSS that extends CSS syntax with numerous		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifeatures, including rule nesting, variable definition, includes, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imathematical operations. Key functionalities can be explored in the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hOfficial Getting Started Guide	URL:https://sass-lang.com/guide	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i. Sass originally used the .sass file extension with a YAML-like		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istructure that wasn't fully compatible with traditional CSS. The		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icurrent Sass format (.scss) maintains full CSS compatibility.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iI use Sass for two primary reasons: First, for clearer CSS rule		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imanagement. For example, when I have CSS rules that only apply to the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwebsite header, I can group them within a single block:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  header {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      h1 { ... }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSecond, to reduce CSS file size during page loading. Although my site		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iuses Bootstrap, I only utilize a small portion of its features (grid		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isystem, navigation bar, and dropdowns). By selectively including		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icomponents, unnecessary CSS isn't loaded. Additionally, I've		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icustomized Bootstrap's colors and shapes using `!important` overrides,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhich adds extra code.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn my .scss files, I define global control colors and font sizes while		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iselectively including Bootstrap's .scss files. By commenting out		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iunused features, the final CSS file size is significantly reduced.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSass also compiles CSS into a single minified file for server		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ideployment.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSimilarly, I use Webpack to eliminate unused Bootstrap JavaScript		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifeatures and compress/merge JS code into a single file. Another		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iadvantage is that Sass and Webpack integrate with npm, allowing me to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iupdate frameworks like Bootstrap and use them consistently across Sass		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand Webpack JS files.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
